    evidenceAnalysis: 'The record included Treasury Department administrative history dating to 1898, demonstrating a consistent practice of not treating indirect tax remissions as countervailable. GATT Secretariat materials and negotiating history of the subsidies provisions were introduced to establish the international understanding of border tax adjustments. Economic analyses comparing the Japanese Commodity Tax burden on domestically sold versus exported televisions were submitted, though the Court found these economic arguments insufficient to overcome Treasury\'s legal interpretation. Industry sales and market share data showed that Japanese television imports had dramatically increased during the 1970s, providing context for Zenith\'s competitive concerns.',
    alternativeOutcomes: 'Had the Supreme Court affirmed the CCPA and required countervailing duties on indirect tax remissions, the United States would have been the first major trading nation to treat standard border tax adjustments as countervailable subsidies, placing it in direct conflict with GATT obligations and potentially triggering a broader trade dispute with Japan and other export-oriented economies. Such a ruling would have also disrupted the Tokyo Round Subsidies Code negotiations then underway. Conversely, the ruling as decided left U.S. manufacturers exposed to competition from countries that remitted indirect taxes—a concern that Congress ultimately addressed through subsequent legislation.',
