    significance: 'Zenith Radio Corp. v. United States is the Supreme Court\'s foundational decision on the scope of U.S. countervailing duty law and the treatment of indirect tax remissions in international trade. It established the principle of strong judicial deference to longstanding agency interpretations in the complex domain of trade remedies and confirmed that U.S. trade statutes should be read in harmony with GATT obligations. The case arose at the height of the U.S.-Japan trade disputes of the 1970s and presaged the broader political controversy over trade imbalances in electronics and automobiles that dominated trade policy for the next two decades. It remains a leading authority in the trade remedies literature and illustrates the interplay between domestic courts, administrative agencies, and international trade law in shaping trade policy.',
